Dataset

For the dataset of this assignment, I used the dataset from kaggle, which is about the Online Gaming Anxiety. This dataset contains variables which indicate the anxiety, life satisfaction, social anxiety ,narcissism, gaming habits, and demographic information of the participants. This dataset is available online. The original data was collected by Marian Sauter and Dejan Draschkow.

Variables and Descriptions

The dataset includes several questionnaires. The variables(or concepts) are as follows:

  • Anxiety : The Generalized Anxiety Disorder 7(GAD-7), which is a 7-item questionnaire to measure the anxiety level of the participants, with higher score indicating higher anxiety level.

  • Life Satisfaction : The Satisfaction with Life Scale (SWLS), which is a 5-item questionnaire to measure the life satisfaction of the participants, with higher score indicating higher life satisfaction.

  • Social Anxiety : The Social Phobia Inventory (SPIN), which is a 17-item questionnaire to measure the social anxiety disorder of the participants, with higher score indicating higher social anxiety.

  • Narcissism : The Single Item Narcissism Scale, which is a questionnaire to measure the narcissism of the participants, with higher score indicating higher narcissism.

  • Gaming Habits : this concepts was measured by different variables:

    • Platform : this variable indicates the platform which the participants are currently using.

    • Hours : this variable indicates the average hours the participants spend on gaming per week.

    • Game : this variable indicates the game which the participants are currently played the most. Meanwhile, only the top 10 games are distributed in the dataset, the rest are displayed as Other.

  • Demographics : this include Gender,Age, Work Status, Education Level, Birth Country, and Country of Residence.

The above information is what I could find about the dataset. However, there are more variables that I could not find any explanations, such as the Zeitstempel, highestleague variable. Using and explaining unspecific variables may result in misinterpretation of the results. Therefor, Those variables without any explanations are not included in the analysis.

Research Questions

As the dataset contains a lot of variables involves Gaming and Anxiety. I would like to explore the relationship between gaming habit and the rest of the variables. The research questions are as follows:

  • RQ1: what is the relationship between gaming hours and anxiety (Do people get more anxious when they spend more time on gaming?)

  • RQ2: In the variables we collected, which variables will contribute to the anxiety level(what will cause a higher anxiety level)?

  • RQ3: Is there a gender difference in social anxiety caused by gaming habits?

As we can see, there are a lot of redundant variables in the dataset(for example, the dataset include every answer for the questionare, but we only need the summarize variable for each sub questionare). We will remove those variables which is not used in the analysis.

# remove the variables which is not used in the analysis
# the subset function allows us to select the variables we want to keep, the "select" argument is used to specify the variables we want to keep
tided_data = subset(raw_data,select = c("Game","Platform","Hours","Narcissism","Gender","Age","Work","Degree","Playstyle","GAD_T","SWL_T","SPIN_T","Residence_ISO3","Birthplace_ISO3"))

Data wrangling

Here, we want to check the missing values in the dataset.

# check the missing values in the dataset
vis_dat(tided_data)

Theres only a few missing values in the dataset(0.5% of missing value if we use vis_mis() function, The reason we use vis_dat() function is that the plot generated by the function will also provide information about the type of the data, This information can help us to reset factor level in the next step). We will remove those missing values.

# remove the missing values
tided_data = na.omit(tided_data)

# This time, we use vis_dat function to check the missing values, because it

Then, we want to reset the character type of the variables to factor type, and re-level the factor for the requirement of meaningful analysis.

# reset the "character" type of the variables to "factor" type
tided_data = tided_data %>%
  mutate(Game = as.factor(Game),
         Platform = as.factor(Platform),
         Gender = as.factor(Gender),
         Work = as.factor(Work),
         Degree = as.factor(Degree),
         Playstyle = as.factor(Playstyle),
         Residence_ISO3 = as.factor(Residence_ISO3),
         Birthplace_ISO3 = as.factor(Birthplace_ISO3))
# re-level the factor for the requirement of meaningful analysis
levels(tided_data$Gender)

Then, we will use the corrplot package and Hmisc package to calculate and generate the correlation matrix.

# as some of the variables are factor variables, we need to convert them to numeric variables before we calculate the correlation matrix.
# lapply function is used to apply the function to each column of the dataset. Here, we use the as.numeric function to convert the factor variables to numeric variables.
correlation_data = as.data.frame(lapply(tided_data,as.numeric))
# calculate the correlation matrix
# rcorr function is used to calculate the correlation matrix. It requies the input to be a matrix, therefore, we use the as.matrix function to convert the dataset to a matrix.
# As we are using data converted from factors, we use the spearman correlation instead of pearson correlation to calculate the correlation matrix.
correlation_matrix = rcorr(as.matrix(correlation_data),type = "spearman")
# extract the correlation coefficient and the p-value from the correlation matrix, and round the correlation coefficient to 2 decimal places(There is not enough room for longer decimal places in the plot).
cors = round(correlation_matrix$r,2)
# extract the p-value from the correlation matrix
mat = correlation_matrix$P
# replace the NA value in the p-value matrix with 0, otherwise the corrplot function will retuen an error.
mat[is.na(mat)] = 0
# plot the correlation matrix
# corrplot function is used to plot the correlation matrix. the meaning of each parameter can be found in the corrplot package using ?corrplot.
corrplot(
  # correlation coefficient matrix
  cors,
  # p-value matrix
  p.mat = mat,
  # plot the upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  # method = "shade" selects the visualization method. Here, we use the shade method(simplely because it looks better than the other methods).
  method = "shade",
  # plot the upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  type = 'upper',
  # insig = 'blank' means that the correlation coefficient which is not significant will be displayed as blank.
  insig = 'blank',
  # add the correlation coefficient on the plot and set the color as black
  addCoef.col = 'black',
  # order the variables based on the hierarchical clustering. This allows us to see the relationship between the variables more clearly.
  order = 'hclust',
  # set the color of the text lables as black
  tl.col = 'black',
  # display the correlation coefficient on the diagonal of the plot
  diag = T,
  # set the position of the text lables as left-top
  tl.pos = 'lt',
  # select cor higher than 0.05 to be displayed.
  sig.level = 0.05,
  # set the size of the text lables as 0.9
  tl.cex = 0.9,
  # let the text lables be rotated by 30 degrees
  tl.srt = 30
) 
# the code below is simillar to the code above, but it plots the lower triangle of the correlation matrix.
# arguements that is the same as the code above is not commented.
  corrplot(
  cors,
  method = "shade",
  type = 'lower',
  addCoef.col = 'black',
  order = 'hclust',
  tl.col = 'black',
  # add = T means that the plot will be added to the previous plot.
  add = T,
  # tl.pos = 'n' means that the text lables will not be displayed(because it's already displayed in the previous plot).
  tl.pos = 'n',
  # cl.pos = 'n' means that the color legend will not be displayed(because it's already displayed in the previous plot).
  cl.pos = 'n'
)
# add the title to the plot
title("Correration Matrix for All Variables")

As in the plot above, the number in each box is the spearman correlation coefficient. In the upper triangle of the plot, the correlation coefficient is displayed only if the p-value is less than 0.05. In the lower triangle of the plot, the correlation coefficient is displayed regardless of the p-value. The color of the box indicates the strength of the correlation (blue indicates positive correlation and red indicates negative correlation).

For research question 1, we focus on the relationship between gaming hours and anxiety. As the plot indicates, the variable Hours is positively correlated with the variable Anxiety(GAD_T) and social anxiety(SPIN_T). This indicates that the more gaming hours a person has, the more likely he/she will have anxiety. However, the correlation coefficient is not very high, which means that the relationship between gaming hours and anxiety is not very strong, and we need to do further analysis to confirm the relationship.

For research question 2,
